<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-11T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-11T19:00:00-05:00" n="40" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1008 b</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-11T19:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            11, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Russian Ambassador to-day informed the Department that he had
                                received yesterday and to-day telegrams from his colleagues at
                                Tokyo, Paris, and London all agreeing in conviction that Japan is
                                preparing to occupy Vladivostok and Khabarovsk. Please discreetly
                                ascertain and report what foundation if any for these suspicions of
                                Russian Ambassadors. Repeat to Peking for similar action.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_PFL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>